          "text": "The user is asking about a Git warning message:\n\n\"warning: in the working copy of 'AGENTS.md', LF will be replaced by CRLF the next time Git touches it\"\n\nThis is a Git warning about line ending normalization. LF = Line Feed (Unix style, \\n), CRLF = Carriage Return + Line Feed (Windows style, \\r\\n).\n\nGit on Windows by default has `core.autocrlf = true`, which means it converts LF to CRLF when checking out files, and CRLF to LF when committing. The file `AGENTS.md` was committed with LF line endings, but Git's autocrlf setting wants to convert it to CRLF on checkout.\n\nThe warning says: \"the next time Git touches it\" — next checkout or add operation will convert LF to CRLF.\n\nThis is normal on Windows. It's just informational. If they want to suppress it, they can:\n1. Set `core.autocrlf = false` — but then mixed line endings can happen\n2. Add a `.gitattributes` file with `* text=auto` — best practice\n3. Or ignore it — it's harmless\n\nLet me explain briefly since I'm in plan mode.",
